  "tldr": [
    {
      "source": "lobsters",
      "subsource": "lobste.rs/ai",
      "category": "ai",
      "title": "Investigating idiosyncrasies in AI fiction",
      "url": "https://arxiv.org/abs/2604.03136",
      "discuss_url": "https://lobste.rs/s/hjuopb",
      "score": 3,
      "comments": 2,
      "author": "kehn",
      "published": "2026-07-02T12:02:29Z",
      "bullets": [
        "LLM-generated fiction exhibits distinct stylistic fingerprints, like repetitive transition phrases, vocabulary biases, and predictable narrative arcs due to RLHF alignment.",
        "Analyzing these idiosyncrasies enables the development of detection heuristics and stylometric classifiers to differentiate machine-generated prose from human-authored fiction.",
        "Mitigating these tropes requires fine-tuning on diverse literary datasets, temperature adjustments, or custom system prompts to suppress overrepresented token sequences."
      ]
    },
    {
      "source": "lobsters",
